<p>
  Colombia is the world's third-largest coffee producer (after Brazil and Vietnam) and the <strong>largest producer growing exclusively arabica</strong>. Annual production reaches 12–14 million bags (60kg each), making coffee one of Colombia's most important exports. But Colombia is far more than volume — it is one of the specialty world's most important origins for consistent, high-quality arabica with a distinctive flavor profile.
</p>

<p>
  Colombia's coffee is defined by <strong>balance</strong>. Unlike Ethiopia's floral drama or Kenya's vivid acidity, Colombian coffee occupies a middle ground that makes it accessible, versatile, and endlessly pleasant. Caramel sweetness, nutty warmth, clean acidity, and milk chocolate — Colombian cups tend toward harmony rather than extremes. This balance, combined with consistent quality infrastructure, has made Colombia the world's most globally recognized coffee origin.
</p>

<div class="info-box">
  <h4>Colombia at a Glance</h4>
  <p>
    <strong>Key varieties:</strong> Castillo, Colombia, Caturra, Bourbon, Typica, Gesha (specialty)<br />
