<h2>Why Colombia Is Unique</h2>

<p>
  Three geographic factors make Colombia extraordinary for coffee:
</p>

<p>
  <strong>The Andes mountain system.</strong> Three Andean ranges (cordilleras) run north-south through Colombia, creating thousands of kilometers of ideal elevation between 1,200m and 2,300m. This produces a staggering number of distinct microclimates, each with its own soil chemistry, temperature profile, and rainfall pattern.
</p>

<p>
  <strong>Proximity to the equator with elevation variation.</strong> Colombia straddles the equator. At low altitudes, it would be too hot for quality arabica. But the Andes provide high altitude at tropical latitude — year-round warmth, no frost, slow cherry maturation. The result: coffee with complexity that temperate-zone producers can't replicate.
</p>

<p>
  <strong>Year-round harvest.</strong> The equatorial position, combined with the north-south orientation of growing regions at different latitudes, means Colombia produces coffee in virtually every month of the year. The main northern harvest (Antioquia, Huila) runs October–February; the Medellin/Bogotá region peaks April–June; the southern regions peak again June–September. Colombia is one of the few origins that can supply fresh crop coffee to buyers 12 months a year.
</p>

