<h2>Varieties</h2>

<p>
  Colombia's varietals tell a story of disease management alongside quality development:
</p>

<p>
  <strong>Caturra</strong> — a natural Bourbon dwarf mutation, introduced to Colombia in the 1950s. Compact, high-yielding, suited to intensive cultivation. Classic Colombian flavor: balanced, caramel, clean. Susceptible to leaf rust.
</p>

<p>
  <strong>Colombia variety</strong> — developed by Cenicafé (the National Coffee Research Center) and introduced in 1982. Resistant to coffee leaf rust. Solid cup quality, though considered less complex than Caturra by specialty buyers.
</p>

<p>
  <strong>Castillo</strong> — Cenicafé's second major disease-resistant variety (2005). Excellent leaf rust resistance, good yields. Cup quality is respectable; controversial among specialty buyers who prefer Caturra's more expressive profile but acknowledge the practical importance of Castillo for farmer economics.
</p>

<p>
  <strong>Bourbon and Typica</strong> — older varieties with exceptional cup quality but disease vulnerability and lower yields. Found primarily at high altitudes in specialty-focused farms willing to accept the agronomic risk for quality.
</p>

<p>
  <strong>Gesha (Geisha)</strong> — the specialty world's most expensive variety, originally from Ethiopia. Colombian Gesha lots from Huila and Antioquia have won international competitions and command extraordinary prices.
</p>

<h2>Processing</h2>

<p>
  Colombia predominantly uses <strong>washed (wet) processing</strong>, traditionally in small farm-based "beneficios" (processing facilities). The typical Colombian washed process uses a unique system called <strong>"desmucilaginado mecánico"</strong> (mechanical demucilaging) — a machine that removes mucilage without fermentation, using water and friction. This approach is faster than tank fermentation and reduces water consumption.
</p>

<p>
  The growing specialty movement has brought more diverse processing to Colombia. <strong>Natural and honey processing</strong> have expanded in Huila and Nariño, particularly among producers supplying specialty buyers directly. Anaerobic fermentation experiments are increasingly common in competition-oriented lots.
</p>

<h2>Flavor Profile</h2>

<p>
  Standard Colombian washed coffee delivers what specialty buyers call a <strong>"clean, balanced, all-day drinker"</strong>:
</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Acidity:</strong> Bright but approachable — malic acid (apple-like) and citric acid in balance, never harsh</li>
  <li><strong>Sweetness:</strong> Caramel, brown sugar, red apple, milk chocolate</li>
  <li><strong>Body:</strong> Medium — substantial enough to be satisfying, light enough to stay versatile</li>
  <li><strong>Finish:</strong> Clean, sweet, lingering without astringency</li>
</ul>

<p>
  High-altitude specialty lots from Huila, Nariño, and Cauca add complexity — more fruit, more florals, more layered acidity — while maintaining the foundational Colombian cleanness. These lots are where Colombia competes directly with Ethiopia and Kenya at the top tier of the specialty market.
</p>

<h2>FNC and the Juan Valdez Brand</h2>

<p>
  No discussion of Colombian coffee is complete without the <strong>Federación Nacional de Cafeteros (FNC)</strong> — the National Coffee Federation founded in 1927. The FNC represents Colombia's ~550,000 coffee farmers, operates extension services, manages quality research through Cenicafé, and runs the famous <strong>Juan Valdez</strong> marketing campaign (launched 1958) that made "Colombian coffee" synonymous with quality in global consumer consciousness.
</p>

<p>
  The FNC's role is controversial in the specialty world — its mandatory participation requirements and collective pricing models don't always align with premium specialty pricing for individual lots. But its foundational investment in infrastructure, variety development, and farmer support has enabled Colombia's consistent quality at scale.
</p>

